RATIONALE

public static final RationaleElementType RATIONALE
A type of RATIONALE specifies the root of our rationale tree. It isn't actually an element type.

REQUIREMENT

public static final RationaleElementType REQUIREMENT
Requirements are things our system is required to do

DECISION

public static final RationaleElementType DECISION
Decisions are decision problems that need to be solved in order to define and implement our system.

ARGUMENT

public static final RationaleElementType ARGUMENT
Arguments argue for and against alternatives for addressing the decisions. They can also argue for and against requirements and about other arguments

ALTERNATIVE

public static final RationaleElementType ALTERNATIVE
Alternatives are alternative solutions to the decision problem. They should eventually map so some sort of developed artifact (code, diagrams, etc.) where the alternative is implemented

CLAIM

public static final RationaleElementType CLAIM
Claims are claims we are making about an alternative within an argument

ASSUMPTION

public static final RationaleElementType ASSUMPTION
Assumptions are things we think are true but that may not always hold true in the future

ONTENTRY

public static final RationaleElementType ONTENTRY
Ontology entries appear in the Argument Ontology and are usually generic non-functional requirements (such as safety or scalability)

TRADEOFF

public static final RationaleElementType TRADEOFF
Tradeoffs refer to two ontology entries where if we want more of one, we need less of the other. Flexibility vs. cost, for example.

COOCCURRENCE

public static final RationaleElementType COOCCURRENCE
Co-occurences refer to two ontology entries where if one is true, the other must be also.

QUESTION

public static final RationaleElementType QUESTION
Questions are things that need to be answered in order to select an alternative or make a decision

DESIGNPRODUCTENTRY

public static final RationaleElementType DESIGNPRODUCTENTRY
Design product entries are components of the product being designed

CONSTRAINT

public static final RationaleElementType CONSTRAINT
Constraints limit the choices we can make when developing a design component. For example, we may have a weight limit for part of a spacecraft.

CONTINGENCY

public static final RationaleElementType CONTINGENCY
Contingencies are added to account for uncertainty. For example, we may have a mass contingency for part of a spacecraft of 20% as a safety margin. The more is known about the design choice being made, the smaller the contingency is likely to be.

DESIGNER

public static final RationaleElementType DESIGNER
The designer is the person writing the rationale.

EXPERTISE

public static final RationaleElementType EXPERTISE
Expertise is an area of expertise that may be held by a designer

ALTCONSTREL

public static final RationaleElementType ALTCONSTREL
The alternative-constraint relationship refers to the relationship between an alternative and a constraint - how much does this particular constraint refer to this alternative?

CANDIDATE

public static final RationaleElementType CANDIDATE
We've added a new type for elements that are candidate rationale not yet adopted

NONE

public static final RationaleElementType NONE
None - should this be occuring?

PATTERN

public static final RationaleElementType PATTERN
This is the actual pattern in the pattern library.

PATTERNDECISION

public static final RationaleElementType PATTERNDECISION
This is the decisions inside a pattern. (those created by default)

ALTERNATIVEPATTERN

public static final RationaleElementType ALTERNATIVEPATTERN
This is the alternative s inside a pattern.
